   # Network security
- DMZ is the perimeter networkthat sits between the internet and the internal network
- we put the system wich puclic facing servers that are more likely to be attacked or compromised
- Without a DMZ: attacker is often already “inside” the internal network or very close to it.
- With a DMZ: attacker lands in a limited zone with restricted paths to internal systems.
## virtual private network(VPN)
- allos remote users to connect securely to the network over the internet
- The user is on an untrusted network (home Wi-Fi, restaurant, mobile data).
- VPN creates an encrypted tunnel to your organization (typically to the firewall).
- After authentication, that remote user behaves almost like they’re inside the internal network,
depending on access rules
## DMZ
   - Vulnerable app or plugin
   - Weak admin interface exposed
   - Poor patching / misconfiguration
   - Leaked credentials in config files
- VPN
   - Stolen credentials (phishing, reuse, password spraying)
   - MFA fatigue / social engineering
   - Misconfigured VPN access (too broad)
   - Compromised remote device connecting legitimately
- Internal users
   - Phishing → session/token theft
   - Malicious attachment / drive-by download
   - Stolen cookies/SSO tokens → access without password
- firewall 
   - can be access firewall settings through WEb admin panel, SSH or CLI management
   - Web admin panel (GUI)
   - SSH  Admin connects remotely using a secure terminal connection.
   - CLI (Command Line Interface) CLI is the text-based way to configure the firewall using commands.
- Reverse Proxy / Load Balancer ,These systems sit in front of servers and receive all incoming traffic.
   - Functions:Forward requests to backend servers Hide internal server IPs -Distribute traffic
- WAF / API Gateway WAF (Web Application Firewall) protects web apps from attacks.
   - possible attacks SQL injection , Cross site scripting (XSS)
   - malicious API calls
- Mail gate way/ STMP relay
   - Functions , spam filtering ,routing email, malware scanning
   - Intenet then mail gateway then internal mailserver . that is the parth 
-DNS
   - if the DNS is authoritative means it is  publicly reachable
   - if DNS recursive/ internal ,it is for internal devices only
   -authoritative DNS servers must be public, they are common targets for attackers.
- Remote access gate way 
   - ex VPN gateways 
   -risk ca be stolen credentials , compromised laptops and weak authentication
- Bastions /Jump Host -Secure server used to access internal system
   - admins connect here first then to other servers
   - Admin then Bastion Host then internal server
- STFP /FTP server
   - used to secure filr trasfer between systems or partners
- VDI/Citrix Gateway
   - provide vietual desktop or remote application
   - users connect to a remote desktop environment hosted in the company network
   - user then citrix gateway then virtual desktop
- VoIP/ SIP Gateway
   - handles internet phone systems
   - SIP protocol allows voice calls over IP network
   - Internet phone network → SIP gateway → internal phone system
- Partner / vendor portal
   - web portal used by external partners or suppliers
- NTP 
   - It is a protocol used to synchronize the clocks of computers and network devices over a network so they all have the same accurate time.
